  { key: 'high-ev-domains', title: 'Highest-EV problem domains (broad scan)',
    task: `Scan broadly for the highest-expected-value hackathon domains for a SOLO builder in 6h that are NOT nonprofit/civic: dev-tools & agentic infra, B2B back-office workflows that take weeks today (claims, loan servicing, underwriting, contracts, compliance, QA), creative/generative tools, data-ops, code migration/refactor swarms, browser/computer-use automation. For each: the pain, who pays, why it's demo-able, and which showcases Opus 4.8 + orchestration best. Rank by (impact x demo-ability x feasibility-solo-6h).` },
  { key: 'back-office-workflows', title: 'Back-office / claims / loan-servicing / contract workflows',
    task: `Research specific back-office workflows that take days/weeks today and could be collapsed to minutes with an agent swarm: insurance claims triage, loan servicing, underwriting, contract review/redlining, invoice/AP, KYC/compliance, RFP response, due diligence. Find concrete, documented process pain + any public sample data/documents we could legally use for a demo. Which one has the cleanest "weeks -> minutes" live demo?` },
  { key: 'agent-swarm', title: 'The swarm: agents on a real backlog / codebase',
    task: `Research the "swarm" thought-starter: point a team of agents at a real backlog/codebase and ship a release. Find compelling, demo-able versions: automated PR-fixing, test-writing, dependency migration, codemod at scale, issue-triage-to-merged-PR, legacy-code modernization. What public repos/backlogs could be the live target? What makes this read as orchestration mastery to judges?` },
  { key: 'dynamic-workflows', title: 'Claude Code dynamic workflows & orchestration mechanics',
